Project: Delivery PoC Web App

Purpose
This is a proof-of-concept delivery web app for drivers.
It is designed to let an admin create a run from an Excel export, generate a driver web link + QR code, and let the driver mark deliveries as delivered or no delivery from a mobile phone.

Tech Stack
- Python
- FastAPI
- Cloud Run (Google Cloud)
- Firestore (run + order persistence)
- Google Cloud Storage (POD photo + signature storage)
- Simple server-rendered HTML/CSS/JS, no frontend framework
- Mobile-first browser use

Hosting / Infra
- Hosted on Google Cloud Run
- Firestore is enabled in Native mode
- Cloud Storage bucket is configured through env var POD_BUCKET
- Firestore is the source of truth
- In-memory cache may exist for convenience, but persistence must rely on Firestore

Core Business Flow
1. Admin uploads an Excel file exported from an internal system.
2. Excel headers are on row 2, row 1 must be ignored.
3. Required columns are:
   - Order
   - PC
   - CP
   - PL
   - LP
   - Account Name
   - Del Suburb
   - Street
   - Building
4. Admin also enters:
   - Run Number
   - optional Driver Email
   - required POD report email
5. System creates a run, stores it in Firestore, and generates:
   - a driver link
   - a QR code for the driver to scan
6. Driver opens the run on phone and sees a list of orders.
7. Driver clicks an order and gets options:
   - NAVIGATE
   - DELIVER
   - NO DELIVERY
8. DELIVER flow:
   - photo is mandatory
   - multiple photos allowed
   - signature is optional
   - photo(s) and signature are uploaded to Cloud Storage
   - Firestore order state becomes DELIVERED
9. NO DELIVERY flow:
   - reasons include:
     - CUST_NOT_PRESENT
     - OTHER
     - BORED ("I could not be bothered ...") -> intentional easter egg
   - Firestore order state becomes UNDELIVERED
10. Manager dashboard shows all runs, progress, QR, print page, and POD viewer.

Run Rules
- Run Number is required
- Run Number must be numeric only
- Run Number length: 3 to 5 digits
- Same run number can be reused on different dates
- But for the same date, run number must be unique
- If a run with the same number already exists today, user must delete old one before creating new one

Run Expiry
- Each run expires 48 hours after creation
- Expired runs still appear in dashboard
- Expired runs still show QR and print options
- Driver run link should not be usable after expiry

Driver UI Requirements
- Mobile-first
- Summary card at top
- Tabs:
  - Pending
  - Delivered
  - Undelivered
- Show:
  - total orders
  - remaining orders
  - PC undelivered
  - progress bar
- Order cards should be compact and visually consistent
- Card content order:
  - Order
  - Suburb
  - Street + Building merged on one line if possible
  - Account Name
  - PC / CP / PL / LP
- Buttons on order detail page must be:
  - NAVIGATE
  - DELIVER
  - NO DELIVERY

Offline / Resilience
- Driver page caches HTML in localStorage
- If run is unavailable, app offers cached offline view
- Offline mode is view-only fallback, not true offline sync

Manager Dashboard Requirements
- Show all runs
- Order of runs:
  1. Active runs first
  2. Expired runs after
  3. Newest first inside each group
- For each run show:
  - Run Number
  - Driver Email
  - Created time
  - Expiry time
  - Total orders
  - Delivered count
  - Remaining count
  - Undelivered count
  - Progress %
  - QR code
- Buttons:
  - OPEN RUN
  - VIEW POD
  - PRINT QR
  - DELETE RUN
- Delete must require confirmation first

POD Viewer Requirements
- Manager can open a run detail page
- Run detail page shows:
  - Delivered orders
  - Undelivered orders
  - Pending orders
- Delivered orders should show:
  - POD photo links
  - signature link if present
  - delivered timestamp
- Undelivered orders should show:
  - reason
  - note

Print Requirements
- One full printable page per run
- Large QR code at top
- Summary below:
  - Run Number
  - Driver Email
  - Created time
  - Expiry time
  - Run link
  - Total / Delivered / Remaining / Undelivered / Progress

Firestore Data Shape
Collection: runs
Document ID: token

Run doc fields:
- created
- expires_at
- run_number
- driver_email
- pod_email
- updated

Subcollection: orders
Document ID: order number

Order fields:
- _idx
- Order
- Account
- Suburb
- Street
- Building
- PC
- CP
- PL
- LP
- state
- last_update
- undelivered_reason
- undelivered_note
- pod_photos
- signature_url
- delivered_ts
- undelivered_ts

Current Important Constraints
- Keep the app simple and prototype-friendly
- Do not replace everything with a heavy frontend framework unless clearly necessary
- Existing behavior and wording matter
- The easter egg reason "I could not be bothered ..." is intentional and must stay
- The run number and dashboard behavior are important business rules
- Firestore must remain source of truth
- Cloud Storage should store uploaded POD files

What Codex Should Be Careful About
- Do not break mobile browser file upload
- Do not reintroduce broken HTML pattern validation for run number
- Do not rely on RAM for run persistence
- Be careful with JS inside Python f-strings
- Preserve current routes where possible
- Preserve current visual flow unless specifically asked to redesign